### Rules for Frontend

- You must pay attention to visual clarity and contrast. Do not place white text on a white background.
- You must ensure the UX is pleasant. Boxes should grow to fit their contents, etc. 
- When asking the user for sensitive information - you must use password style text-entry boxes in the UI.
- You should use Next.js as it works best with Vercel.
- Follow official Next.js guidance: https://nextjs.org/docs
- This frontend will ultimately be deployed on Vercel, but it should be possible to test locally. 
- Always provide users with a way to run the created UI once you have created it.


## Color Palette
- Primary: Use a deep slate blue (#1E293B) for primary actions.
- Accent: Use a vibrant emerald green (#10B981) for success states and buttons.
- Background: Use a neutral off-white (#F8FAFC) for backgrounds to reduce eye strain.
- Text: Use dark charcoal (#334155) for main headings and soft grey (#64748B) for secondary text.

## Styling Philosophy
- Use Tailwind CSS for all styling.
- Components should have rounded corners (use `rounded-xl` for cards, `rounded-lg` for buttons).
- All buttons should have a subtle hover transition (`transition-all duration-200 hover:scale-105`).
- Use "Glassmorphism" for cards: `bg-white/80 backdrop-blur-md border border-white/20`.

## Best Practices
- Always ensure mobile responsiveness first (mobile-first approach).
- Use Lucide-react for all iconography.
- Maintain consistent padding: use `p-4` for small containers and `p-8` for main sections.
- When in doubt, favor whitespace over clutter.
